Biography of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang

Zhang Tingwei Shizhi was a native of Duyang, with the courtesy name Ji. He had an elder brother named Zhong, with whom he lived. Using his wealth, he became a Cavalry Attendant, serving Emperor Wen of Han. For ten years he received no promotion and was unknown. Shizhi said, "Serving in office for so long diminishes my brother's property; this is not what I desire." He wished to resign and return home. Yuan Ang, the Commandant of the Palace, knew him to be virtuous and regretted his departure, so he requested that Shizhi be transferred to the position of Attendant. After Shizhi had completed the morning audience, he took the opportunity to discuss matters of current expediency. Emperor Wen said, "Keep it low-level; do not engage in high-minded theories. Let it be something that can be implemented now." Thus Shizhi spoke at length about affairs between the Qin and Han dynasties, why the Qin had lost and why the Han had risen. Emperor Wen praised him and appointed Shizhi as Chief of the Attendants.

Shizhi accompanied the Emperor on a tour, ascending the Tiger Enclosure. The Emperor asked the Forester of the Upper Forest about the registers of various birds and beasts. After more than ten questions, the Forester looked left and right and could not answer. The Keeper of the Tiger Enclosure, standing by, answered the Emperor's questions about the registers of birds and beasts in great detail, hoping to demonstrate his ability to respond endlessly with eloquence. Emperor Wen said, "Should an official not be like this? The Forester is useless!" He then ordered Shizhi to appoint the Keeper as Prefect of the Upper Forest. Shizhi approached slowly and said, "Your Majesty, what kind of person is Zhou Bo, the Marquis of Jiang?" The Emperor said, "A man of virtue." Shizhi asked again, "What kind of person is Zhang Xiangru, the Marquis of Dongyang?" The Emperor again said, "A man of virtue." Shizhi said, "Zhou Bo and Zhang Xiangru are called men of virtue, yet these two cannot even speak well in discussion. Are you imitating this Keeper's glib tongue and quick wit? Moreover, the Qin relied on officials who dealt with documents and laws; officials competed with each other in being swift, harsh, and critical, but their flaw was merely formalistic compliance, lacking genuine compassion. Therefore, their faults were not heard of, and they declined until the Second Emperor, when the world collapsed. Now Your Majesty promotes this Keeper rapidly because of his eloquence. I fear the world will follow suit, competing in eloquence without substance. Furthermore, the people imitate their superiors as quickly as shadow follows form or echo follows sound; your actions must not be unexamined." Emperor Wen said, "Well said." He stopped and did not appoint the Keeper.

The Emperor boarded his carriage, summoned Shizhi to ride beside him, and walked slowly, asking Shizhi about the flaws of the Qin. Shizhi answered with plain truth. Upon returning to the palace, the Emperor appointed Shizhi as Director of the Carriages and Horses.

Soon after, the Crown Prince and the King of Liang rode together in a carriage into the court and did not dismount at the Gate of the Sima. Shizhi pursued and stopped the Crown Prince and the King of Liang, preventing them from entering the palace gates. He then impeached them for failing to dismount at the public gate, showing disrespect, and submitted the memorial. Empress Dowager Bo heard of this. Emperor Wen removed his cap and apologized, saying, "I failed to educate my sons carefully." Empress Dowager Bo then sent an envoy to convey the edict pardoning the Crown Prince and the King of Liang, after which they were allowed to enter. From this, Emperor Wen considered Shizhi extraordinary and appointed him as Grand Master.

Soon after, he rose to the position of Commandant of the Palace. He accompanied the Emperor to the Baling Mausoleum, which was situated to the north overlooking a toilet. At that time, Lady Shen was accompanying the Emperor. The Emperor pointed out the road to Xinfeng to Lady Shen and said, "This is the road to Handan." He had Lady Shen play the se, and leaning on the se, he sang himself. His mood was sad and sorrowful. He looked at his ministers and said, "Alas! If we use stones from Mount Bei for the outer coffin, and pack hemp fibers around it, sealing the gaps with lacquer, could it be moved?" Those around him said, "Well said." Shizhi stepped forward and said, "If there is something desirable inside, even if you seal it with the stones of Mount Nan, there will still be gaps; if there is nothing desirable inside, even without a stone coffin, what is there to grieve?" Emperor Wen praised him. Later, Shizhi was appointed as Tingwei (Minister of Justice).

Soon after, the Emperor went out to the Middle Wei Bridge. A person emerged from under the bridge, startling the Emperor's carriage horses. The Emperor ordered cavalry to arrest him and handed him over to the Tingwei. Shizhi investigated and questioned him. The man said, "A resident of the county came here, heard the imperial procession was coming, and hid under the bridge. After a long time, thinking the procession had passed, he came out, saw the imperial carriage and cavalry, and ran away." The Tingwei Qin sentenced him: "One who violates the imperial procession should be fined." Emperor Wen was angry and said, "This person personally startled my horses. If my horses had not been gentle, and another horse had been startled, would it not have caused me harm? Yet the Tingwei sentences him only to a fine!" Shizhi said, "The law is what the Son of Heaven shares with the world. Now if the law is such and yet we make it heavier, the law will lose credibility with the people. Moreover, at that moment, if Your Majesty had ordered him to be executed on the spot, it would have been done. But now that he has been handed over to the Tingwei, the Tingwei is the balance of the world. If it tilts, everyone in the world will use the law with varying degrees of severity, and where will the people place their hands and feet? I beg Your Majesty to consider this." After a long time, the Emperor said, "The Tingwei's judgment is correct."

Later, someone stole the jade ring from the front of the altar of Emperor Gaozu. He was captured. Emperor Wen was angry and handed him over to the Tingwei for trial. Shizhi investigated the law regarding theft of ritual vessels and imperial garments and submitted a memorial recommending the death penalty by exposure in the market. The Emperor was furious and said, "How wicked! This man stole the vessels of the Late Emperor. I handed him to the Tingwei because I wanted him to be exterminated to his clan, yet you submit a legal judgment. This is not my intention in reverently serving the Ancestral Temple." Shizhi removed his cap and kowtowed, apologizing, saying, "The law is sufficient as it is. Moreover, for crimes of the same degree, there is a difference based on the degree of opposition. If we exterminate to the clan for stealing ancestral temple vessels, what if, one in ten thousand times, a foolish commoner took a handful of earth from Changling Mausoleum? How would Your Majesty increase the punishment?" After a long time, Emperor Wen discussed it with the Empress Dowager, and then agreed with the Tingwei's judgment. At that time, the Commandant, Marquis Tiaohou Zhou Yafu, and the Chancellor of Liang, Marquis Shandu Wang Tiankai, saw that Shizhi's judgments were fair, and they formed close friendships with him. Zhang Tingwei was thus praised by the world.

After Emperor Wen died, Emperor Jing ascended the throne. Shizhi was afraid and claimed illness. He wanted to resign, fearing a great purge; he wanted to appear and apologize, but did not know how. Following Wang Sheng's advice, he finally appeared and apologized. Emperor Jing did not reprimand him.

Wang Sheng was good at speaking about Huang-Lao philosophy and was a recluse. He was once summoned to the court. When the Three Excellencies and the Nine Ministers were all standing together, Wang Sheng, an old man, said, "My sandal strap is loose," and looked at Zhang Tingwei, saying, "Tie my sandal strap for me!" Shizhi knelt and tied it. Afterward, someone said to Wang Sheng, "How could you humiliate Zhang Tingwei in front of everyone, making him kneel to tie your sandal strap?" Wang Sheng said, "I am old and lowly, and I know I can ultimately do nothing to help Zhang Tingwei. Zhang Tingwei is currently a famous minister of the world. I deliberately humiliated him, making him kneel to tie my sandal strap, in order to enhance his reputation." When the nobles heard this, they esteemed Wang Sheng and respected Zhang Tingwei.

Zhang Tingwei served Emperor Jing for over a year and was appointed Chancellor of Huainan, still bearing the blame for his previous offense. After a long time, Shizhi died. His son was Zhang Zhi, with the courtesy name Changgong. He rose to the rank of Daifu but was dismissed. Because he could not flatter the contemporary powers, he never held office again.

Feng Tang's grandfather was from Zhao. His father moved to Dai. When the Han dynasty rose, they moved to Anling. Tang was known for his filial piety and served as Chief of the Bureau of Palace Attendants, serving Emperor Wen. One day, Emperor Wen's carriage passed by and asked Tang, "Old man, how did you become a Lang? Where is your home?" Tang answered truthfully. Emperor Wen said, "When I lived in Dai, my Supervisor of Imperial Meals, Gao Qu, often told me about the excellence of Li Qi, the general of Zhao, who fought below Julu. Now, every time I eat, I think of Julu. Do you know him?" Tang replied, "He is not as good as Lian Po and Li Mu as generals." The Emperor said, "Why?" Tang said, "My grandfather, when in Zhao, served as a commander and was good friends with Li Mu. My father was formerly the Chancellor of Dai and was good friends with Zhao's general Li Qi, knowing his character." After hearing about Lian Po and Li Mu, the Emperor was greatly pleased and slapped his thigh, saying, "Alas! If only I had Lian Po and Li Mu as my generals now, would I not worry about the Xiongnu!" Tang said, "Your servant fears! Even if Your Majesty had Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not use them." The Emperor was angry, stood up, and entered the inner palace. After a long time, he summoned Tang and reprimanded him, "How could you humiliate me in public? Is there no private place?" Tang apologized, "This humble one does not know the taboos."

At that time, the Xiongnu had recently invaded Chaona in large numbers, killing Bingyi, the Commandant of Beidi. The Emperor was concerned about the Hu invaders and finally asked Tang again, "How do you know I cannot use Lian Po and Li Mu?" Tang replied, "I have heard that in ancient times, when kings sent out generals, they knelt and pushed the carriage wheel, saying, 'Within the gates, I control it; outside the gates, the general controls it. Military merits and ranks are decided outside, and reported upon return. This is not empty talk.' My grandfather said that when Li Mu was a general of Zhao stationed at the border, the rent from the military markets was used entirely to entertain the soldiers, and rewards were decided outside, without interference from the center. Entrusting them with responsibility and demanding success, Li Mu was able to exhaust his wisdom and ability. He dispatched 1,300 chariots, 13,000 bow-riding cavalry, and 100,000 soldiers of a hundred gold, thereby driving back the Chanyu to the north, defeating the Donghu, destroying the Danlin, suppressing the strong Qin to the west, and supporting Han and Wei to the south. At that time, Zhao was nearly hegemonic. Later, King Qian of Zhao ascended the throne; his mother was a singer. When King Qian ascended, he used the slander of Guo Kai and ultimately executed Li Mu, ordering Yan Ju to replace him. Thus the army was broken and the soldiers fled, and Zhao was captured and destroyed by Qin. Now I secretly hear that Wei Shang, the Commandant of Yunzhong, uses all the rent from the military markets to entertain the soldiers, and spends his private money to feed them, beating a cow every five days to entertain guests, military officers, and retainers. Thus the Xiongnu stay far away and do not approach the Yunzhong pass. Once the enemy entered, Wei Shang led chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many. The soldiers are all sons of common families, rising from the fields to join the army. How would they know the rules of the tally and the regulations? All day they fight hard, beheading enemies and capturing prisoners, reporting their merits to the military headquarters. If one word does not correspond, clerical officials use the law to punish them. Their rewards are not granted, but the officials strictly apply the law. I am foolish, but I think Your Majesty's laws are too clear, rewards too light, and punishments too heavy. Moreover, Wei Shang, Commandant of Yunzhong, was punished for a discrepancy of six heads in his reported enemy kills. Your Majesty handed him over to the officials, stripped his rank, and sentenced him to hard labor. From this, I say, even if Your Majesty had Lian Po and Li Mu, you could not use them. I am truly foolish and have violated taboos. Death, death!" Emperor Wen was pleased. That day, he ordered Feng Tang to carry the tally to pardon Wei Shang, restore him as Commandant of Yunzhong, and appointed Tang as Commandant of Chariots and Cavalry, in charge of the Commandant of the Capital and the cavalry of the commanderies and kingdoms.

In the seventh year, Emperor Jing ascended the throne and appointed Tang as Chancellor of Chu, but he was dismissed. When Emperor Wu ascended, he sought virtuous men and Feng Tang was recommended. Tang was over ninety years old and could no longer serve as an official, so Tang's son, Feng Sui, was made a Lang. Sui's courtesy name was Wangsun. He was also an extraordinary man and was friendly with me.

The Grand Historian says: Zhang Ji's words about men of virtue show that he adhered to the law and did not flatter the will; Feng Gong's discussion of generals is profound! Profound! The saying goes, "If you do not know a person, look at his friends." The praises of these two gentlemen can be recorded in the halls of government. The Book of Documents says, "Unbiased and unpartisan, the King's Way is vast; unpartisan and unbiased, the King's Way is smooth." Zhang Ji and Feng Gong were close to this. [end of text]


